@Prognosticating-Beek Thank you for your thoughtful analysis. I largely agree. Two comments:  1) What are the strategic objectives of Saudi Arabia and Russia? I agree that the primary immediate driver is tit-for-tat strategy. However I think its a mistake to assume that is all. It appears that they are trying to send fear into the market and thereby destabilize competing investments such as US shale. Certainly they aren't doing anything that signals a desire to ease pain or fear for the rest of the market. If that's a goal, we should ask: "how long would it take to put a serious and sustainable dent in US production?"  If that's their goal then I would expect them to keep up wild gyrations and unpredictable and painful behavior for as long as it takes (6 months?) to drive lenders in the US to not view US shale oil as a good investment. Russia and SA both have a huge competitive advantage (among others) in that they don't need to keep bankers happy. 
2) Why are they doing this now? Maybe: now is a good time if you assume prices are going to be down for a while anyway, so you might as well get to the point of fear and capitulation for the marginal producers. I don't think they would have reacted this way in a booming, stable economy. 
3) what will economic growth be in 2020? I don't share your view that the course of the epidemic in Europe and the US will match the quick up and down of round 1 in China. The US is failing at containment and even in Italy the actions appear to fall short so far. More importantly these actions can't be maintained for more than a few months due to the cost. At some point China and other countries need to get back to business and when that happens I fear the virus will come back.
